**Abstract:**
A major essay dated July 22, 1992, titled "Les droits de l'homme" (The Rights of Man), critiquing the Enlightenment conception of universal human rights. The document argues that the "universal individual" of human rights discourse is modeled on the geometric object of contemplation--abstract, stripped of particularities, neither male nor female, Mexican nor American. It connects this to Kant's autonomous, rationally self-motivating individual and argues that history, particularity, and affectivity are systematically excluded. Uses the resurgence of European nationalism as evidence that the repressed particular returns. Develops the distinction between orthodoxia and orthopraxis, arguing for the primacy of the latter.

**AI Recommendation:** Important essay applying the Chantilly project's critique of Greek contemplative categories to political philosophy and human rights discourse.

